==English==

===Etymology===
An [[analogy]] to the spreading ripples on a body of water after an object has struck the surface.

===Noun===
{{en-noun}}

# The circumstance in which one [[event]] [[instigate]]s an [[expansive]] set of other events.
#: {{ux|en|Defaults in America's mortgage lending businesses are causing a '''ripple effect''' through the major banks in other continents.}}
#* {{quote-book|en|year=2016|title=Lying In Wait |author=Liz Nugent |page=115 |ISBN=9781844883639 |passage=Whatever had happened to her, her behaviour had '''ripple effects''' that were still causing upset and grief nearly five years later. }}
#* {{quote-journal|en|author=Lananh Nguyen|title=Global Banks Poised for Turmoil as West Hits Russia With Sanctions|work=The New York Times|date=2022-02-22|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2022/02/22/business/banks-russia-sanctions.html|issn=0362-4331|author2=Alan Rappeport|passage=Global banks are bracing for the '''ripple effects''' of harsh new financial and economic sanctions against Russia intended to hobble its economy and restrict its access to foreign capital.}}

